    "publication": [
        {
            "abstract": "The CRISPR genomic structures (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) form a family of repeats that is largely present in archaea and frequent in bacteria. On the basis of a formal model of CRISPR using very few parameters, a systematic study of all their occurrences in all available genomes of Archaea and Bacteria has been carried out. This has resulted in a relational database, CRISPI, which also includes a complete repertory of associated CRISPR-associated genes (CAS). A user-friendly web interface with many graphical tools and functions allows users to extract results, find CRISPR in personal sequences or calculate sequence similarity with spacers. Â© The Author(s) 2009. Published by Oxford University Press.",
            "authors": [
                "Rousseau C.",
                "Gonnet M.",
                "Le Romancer M.",
                "Nicolas J."
            ],
